vine 1.2.0
prefix: ssm
title: Scout source management
---
[ssm] Generalize scout source onboarding and indexing (planning)
Two scout commands replace the current per-vendor pattern (a bespoke
fetch_modal_docs.py-shaped script per source, a hand-added tuple in
search.py's DOCS_SOURCES, a manual search.py --update run): an idempotent
add-source command that registers a new remote source with a TTL, fetches
it, and indexes it; and a separate refresh-stale command that re-fetches
and re-indexes every already-registered source whose TTL has expired,
replacing today's read-the-warning-then-copy-the-refresh-command manual
loop. Both commands need representation on the CLI and as an MCP tool.
Vine graphs are workspace-authored planning artifacts scout never indexes
today; add them as a first-class chunked corpus alongside spec/notes/
proposals/docs, using structural (per-task) chunking rather than raw word
windows, since a task is already the natural retrievable unit.
-> ssm/design/chunk-adapters
-> ssm/design/command-surface
-> ssm/design/fetch-admission
-> ssm/design/fresh-source-refetch
-> ssm/design/scout-config
-> ssm/design/source-artifact-contract
-> ssm/design/source-lifecycle
-> ssm/design/source-registry
-> ssm/design/vine-chunking
-> ssm/design/vine-corpus
-> ssm/implement/add-source
-> ssm/implement/freshness-presentation
-> ssm/implement/onboarding-migration
-> ssm/implement/refresh-stale
-> ssm/implement/source-control-plane
-> ssm/implement/vine-indexing
-> ssm/verify/source-management
---
[ssm/design/source-artifact-contract] Design source descriptor-to-artifact contract (notstarted)
The public source row is fixed: name, origin URL, type, and ttl_days. The
single sources.json ledger retains that declaration together with fetched
state; there is no separate descriptor entity and no additional public source
fields to choose here. Today search.py needs a corpus and a local artifact
root while the existing fetchers have different collection shapes. The owner
decides the deterministic mapping from the declared row to one corpus and one
artifact location, whether this ledger covers only pinned docs or other
remote corpora too, and the output contract a fetch implementation returns to
the source manager. Settle the vocabulary boundary too: a remote source's
fetch/content type must not be conflated with the independent chunk-adapter
kind introduced in ssm/design/chunk-adapters. The result is the contract
consumed by the ledger, lifecycle, admission, and command-surface designs.
Accept: the owner confirms how every registered source resolves to one corpus,
one artifact location, and one fetch-result shape.
---
[ssm/design/source-registry] Design the source ledger and its CRUD operations (notstarted)
Redefine the source registry as a single ledger -- sources.json's existing role
(fetched-state) absorbs the registry too; there is no separate descriptor
entity. Each record retains the fixed declared row: name, origin URL, type
(the content shape scout should expect back; unset defaults to 'http', a plain
mirror/curl fetch -- no per-source fetch-strategy concept), ttl_days, plus its
fetched state. Callers operate on the ledger via CRUD: one call carries a
batch of rows, each tagged add/update/remove, since ledger changes are
naturally batched (a handful of sources at a time) rather than one at a time.
The ledger stays small by design -- every access reads and locks the whole
file, no partial or indexed access.
Add rows apply directly as source registration, not as a claim that their
artifact has fetched or their index has published; ssm/design/source-lifecycle
owns those later states. Remove and update rows use a crash-safe two-step
protocol: durably append the remove/update intent to the end of the ledger
first, then atomically apply it in one write (deleting both the intent marker
and the target row for a remove; replacing the target for an update). An
interruption between the two steps leaves the intent behind, so the operation
always completes on the next access instead of landing half-done.
The durable intent needs a representation that stays readable and recoverable
on every access; a raw append to a standalone JSON object cannot itself be
that representation. Decide the ledger's one writer and migration boundary:
existing vendor fetchers cannot continue to mutate it through a separate
freshness.stamp path that bypasses locking and recovery. Define source
identity and batch semantics too: duplicate names, divergent same-name adds,
stale re-adds, operation ordering within a batch, and whether a batch reports
per-row partial results or has an atomic outcome.
Needs failure/timeout configuration (lock-wait duration, retry policy) for
ledger access -- see ssm/design/scout-config. Freshness selection must be a
structured result shared by refresh and warning presentation, not a refresh
parser for user-facing warning strings.
-> ssm/design/source-artifact-contract
-> ssm/design/scout-config
---
[ssm/design/source-lifecycle] Design the source artifact-to-index lifecycle (notstarted)
Given the settled registry behavior, decide the artifact-to-index transition
after an added, updated, removed, or refreshed source is registered. A direct
add record is not itself a fetched or searchable success. Current fetchers
can replace an artifact before all remote pages succeed, while freshness only
knows whether an artifact is present; metadata-only crash recovery cannot
distinguish a complete pin from a nonempty partial replacement. The owner
decides the commit/recovery states for a failed fetch, interruption between
durable intent and final state, index-update failure after a successful fetch,
and removal. The result states which stages make a command row successful and
which recovery action occurs on its next access.
Accept: the owner confirms a failure-state table in which no partial artifact
can masquerade as a completed fresh source.
-> ssm/design/source-registry
---
[ssm/design/fetch-admission] Design remote fetch admission and resource policy (notstarted)
Given the source descriptor-to-artifact contract, decide the rules enforced
before Scout fetches a caller-supplied remote origin: accepted URL schemes,
redirect policy, expected content handling, response-size bounds, and the
division between fixed source semantics and tunable Scout operational config.
This task owns enforcement policy; command-surface design only decides how
callers supply a row and receive a rejected or failed outcome. The settled
policy must be usable by the shared control plane for both CLI and MCP calls.
Accept: the owner confirms the admission and resource contract, including how
each refused or exceeded limit is reported without claiming a lifecycle stage
that was not reached.
-> ssm/design/source-artifact-contract
---
[ssm/design/fresh-source-refetch] Decide the fresh-source refetch policy (notstarted)
The current two-command intent says a still-fresh re-add is a no-op and that
refresh-stale selects only stale or absent entries, leaving no settled answer
for an operator who wants to re-fetch a healthy source. The owner decides
whether that operation is intentionally unavailable or belongs within one of
the two public command contracts; do not silently add a third public command
or assign fresh work to a stale-only command. The result tells command-surface
and control-plane work how freshness affects an explicit caller request.
Accept: the owner confirms the behavior of a caller-requested refetch for a
still-fresh source and the result terminology shown on both surfaces.
-> ssm/design/source-lifecycle
---
[ssm/design/vine-chunking] Design per-task chunking for vine files (notstarted)
Given the chunk-type-adapter interface from ssm/design/chunk-adapters, design
vine's adapter: parse a .vine file into its task blocks (reusing bacchus's
vine parser semantics: id, name, status, description, decisions) and emit one
chunk per task, self-citing as "<vine-stem>#<task-id>#vine" (or similar). A
task whose description exceeds comfortable embedding length may still need
internal windowing -- decide whether that stays out of scope for the first cut
or is handled by sub-chunking within a task while preserving the task-id
citation.
Settle the local parser boundary and versioned semantics used at indexing time;
the indexer must not need a live MCP vine_read call to parse a file. A citation
must retain an unambiguous repo-relative file locator plus task id so a result
can resolve back through vine_read even when vine stems collide. A ref block
is a proxy rather than a task: the owner decides whether refs emit chunks at
all; if they do, the adapter must define a distinct ref citation and a
ref-aware resolution contract rather than promise task lookup for a proxy.
Decide how an emitted ref result relates to the referred graph without silently
producing ambiguous duplicates.
-> ssm/design/chunk-adapters
---
[ssm/design/vine-corpus] Decide where vine chunks attach in search.py (notstarted)
Given per-task chunking from ssm/design/vine-chunking, decide which corpus
absorbs vine chunks. Vines are workspace-authored planning text (like spec/
notes/proposals), not third-party material and not vendor docs, so the
workspace corpus is the default candidate -- confirm no separation concern
(a vine task chunk competing against spec/proposal prose in the same
ranked results) forces a fourth corpus instead. Wire the chosen glob
(root localmodal.vine, proposals/**/*.vine, any future vine locations)
into workspace_chunks() alongside the existing spec/notes/proposals/doc
sources, using the chunker from ssm/design/vine-chunking rather than the
existing word-window helper.
-> ssm/design/vine-chunking
---
[ssm/implement/vine-indexing] Implement vine parsing and corpus wiring (notstarted)
Implement the chunk-type-adapter mechanism designed in ssm/design/chunk-adapters, using it to host the vine adapter designed in ssm/design/vine-chunking, wired into workspace_chunks() per the attachment point decided in ssm/design/vine-corpus. Confirm self-citing ids resolve back to a real task via vine_read, the same way a paper/doc citation resolves back to its source page.
Use the settled local parser boundary rather than invoking MCP while building
the index. Test task citations against vine_read; if the settled adapter emits
ref chunks, test their distinct citation against the settled ref-aware
resolution contract rather than treating a ref proxy as a task.
-> ssm/design/chunk-adapters
-> ssm/design/vine-corpus
---
[ssm/design/command-surface] Design the scout command surface (notstarted)
Before any implementation starts, carefully design and encapsulate the two
invocation surfaces: (1) a ledger CRUD command -- takes a batch of rows
(add/update/remove), each row naming a type (default 'http') per
ssm/design/source-registry, applies them to the ledger, fetching and indexing
any added/updated source; (2) refresh all sources past their TTL -- no
argument, scans and re-fetches only stale/missing entries, applying its own
re-fetch results as ledger updates via the same crash-safe protocol. Resolve
the public-name/scope mismatch too: either add-source is the public name for
the full batch CRUD command or the public name changes, so readers never have
to infer whether update and remove are externally available.
Each command needs its own representation on both the CLI and the MCP tool
surface: exact argument shape, output/error contract (per-row success/failure
in a batch), and how both stay isolated from the ledger's internal
locking/crash-safety mechanics in ssm/design/source-registry so those
internals can change without changing either calling contract. Apply the
settled fetch-admission and fresh-source-refetch policies; row outcomes must
name the lifecycle stage reached, not merely conceal a fetch, ledger, or
indexing failure.
Accept: the owner confirms the settled two-command CLI + MCP contract before ssm/implement/add-source and ssm/implement/refresh-stale begin.
-> ssm/design/fetch-admission
-> ssm/design/fresh-source-refetch
-> ssm/design/source-registry
-> ssm/design/source-lifecycle
---
[ssm/design/chunk-adapters] Design chunk-type adapters for scout (notstarted)
Scout's three corpora (papers/docs/workspace) each chunk every source the same
fixed way today: a word-window with overlap, no override. There is no
mechanism for a corpus input to associate its own structural shape with a
chunker. Treat this as a typing problem: design a general chunk-type-adapter
interface -- how a corpus input is assigned a chunk kind, how a corpus
dispatches to the matching adapter instead of the default word-window chunker,
and what an adapter must produce (chunk id, chunk text) to stay compatible
with the existing self-citing-id and indexing pipeline (content-hash _sig,
manifest.json, versioned index publish). Minimize assumptions about the first
consumer: the vine per-task chunker (ssm/design/vine-chunking) is one adapter
instance under this interface, not a special case hardcoded into
workspace_chunks(). A future PDF-structure, code-AST, or other
structured-source adapter should register the same way.
This task does not define a remote source's type field or its fetch behavior;
the source-artifact contract owns that distinct vocabulary boundary.
Accept: the owner confirms one adapter interface shape before ssm/design/vine-chunking is finalized against it.
---
[ssm/implement/source-control-plane] Implement the shared source control plane (notstarted)
Implement the settled config reader, ledger mutation and recovery API,
structured freshness state, and artifact-to-index lifecycle behind one local
control-plane interface. This task owns the shared behavior used by both
source commands; command implementations neither manipulate the ledger nor
derive staleness directly. It owns fetch dispatch, including the declared
default http implementation for a new caller-supplied origin, and routes any
existing vendor fetcher through the same settled result shape; no direct
freshness.stamp mutation bypass remains. Enforce the settled remote
fetch-admission policy and support the settled fresh-source-refetch behavior
through this one interface rather than duplicating either concern in a CLI or
MCP wrapper.
Accept: one operation path owns all ledger writes and recovery, and its output
is sufficient for either CLI or MCP code to report each row's lifecycle state;
the default http type fetches an admitted deterministic fixture through that
same path.
-> ssm/design/fetch-admission
-> ssm/design/fresh-source-refetch
-> ssm/design/scout-config
-> ssm/design/source-lifecycle
-> ssm/design/source-registry
---
[ssm/implement/add-source] Implement the add-source command (notstarted)
Build the settled public batch mutation command from
ssm/implement/source-control-plane and ssm/design/command-surface: given a
batch of rows (add/update/remove, each row naming a type that defaults to
'http'), invoke the settled lifecycle so added/updated sources become
searchable only at the contract's successful stage. Add is idempotent:
re-adding an already-registered, still-fresh source is a no-op (or an explicit
no-op report), never a silent re-fetch. Any caller-requested fresh refetch
follows ssm/design/fresh-source-refetch rather than being assigned to the
stale-only refresh command. Expose the command on both surfaces settled in
ssm/design/command-surface: a CLI subcommand and an MCP tool. Existing vendor
fetchers may remain internal fetch implementations, but each must participate
in the shared control-plane lifecycle.
-> ssm/design/command-surface
-> ssm/implement/source-control-plane
---
[ssm/implement/refresh-stale] Implement the refresh-stale command (notstarted)
Build the refresh command: no source argument, obtain the settled structured
TTL-expired or artifact-absent selection from the shared control plane,
re-fetch each source through its lifecycle, and publish the resulting index
update. Its stale/absent-only scope and any separate caller-requested
fresh-source behavior follow ssm/design/fresh-source-refetch; it never
registers a new source (that is the batch mutation command's job). Expose it
on both surfaces settled in ssm/design/command-surface: a CLI subcommand and
an MCP tool.
-> ssm/design/command-surface
-> ssm/implement/source-control-plane
---
[ssm/implement/onboarding-migration] Migrate source onboarding references (notstarted)
After both public source commands exist, audit the repository's README,
Scout-facing descriptions, command examples, and other user-facing guidance.
Replace instructions that tell a user to create or invoke a vendor-specific
fetch script as the onboarding path with the settled public command contract.
Existing vendor fetch implementations may remain internal and must not be
advertised as the way to register a source. This task owns the documentation
and usage migration only, not the command or control-plane implementation.
Accept: the audit records every changed public reference and finds no remaining
onboarding instruction that requires a new bespoke vendor fetch script.
-> ssm/implement/add-source
-> ssm/implement/refresh-stale
---
[ssm/implement/freshness-presentation] Migrate freshness warnings to the public refresh path (notstarted)
Adapt the search-facing freshness warning consumer to consume the structured
freshness state from ssm/implement/source-control-plane. A stale or absent
source must still scream in the affected corpus results, but its recovery
guidance must use the settled public refresh-stale command contract rather
than a source-specific fetch-script string. This task owns presentation and
search-worker wiring only; it does not select stale sources or mutate the
ledger.
Accept: a stale and an absent deterministic fixture each produce a corpus
warning that names the public recovery path, and neither warning exposes a
legacy per-vendor refresh command.
-> ssm/design/command-surface
-> ssm/implement/source-control-plane
-> ssm/implement/refresh-stale
---
[ssm/design/scout-config] Design where scout's own operational config lives (notstarted)
Scout needs operational settings beyond source data itself -- ledger lock-wait
timeout, retry/failure policy for the CRUD protocol in
ssm/design/source-registry, and any resource bounds the settled fetch-admission
policy classifies as tunable. Design where this config lives: a checked-in file
in the repo (not environment variables, not hardcoded constants), its shape,
and how search.py and the CLI/MCP command surface read it. Keep it distinct
from sources.json (which stays pure ledger data, not Scout's own operating
parameters).
-> ssm/design/fetch-admission
---
[ssm/verify/source-management] Verify source-management failure and recovery behavior (notstarted)
Exercise the settled contract with deterministic local fixtures rather than
live vendor traffic. Cover interrupted ledger intent recovery, a failed fetch
that leaves no partial artifact looking like a completed fresh source, an
index-update failure with its specified recovery state, batch outcome
reporting, idempotent add behavior, the settled caller-requested fresh-source
behavior, refresh selection limited to stale or absent sources, and the
default http fetch path. Exercise both CLI and MCP representations against the
same control-plane result contract, plus the search-facing warning presentation
for stale and absent fixtures.
Accept: the evidence records each scenario's observed lifecycle state and
shows no command reports searchable success before the source is searchable.
-> ssm/implement/add-source
-> ssm/implement/freshness-presentation
-> ssm/implement/refresh-stale
